Okay, I hung up the new nest box today. This is how it looks at its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: „What exactly is inside?“
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fish-eye lens and an IR-LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swivel side wall of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there's no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here's a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse, the battery is located.
When it's charged, I get about 4 hours of run time.
That's what I call a feature. So the birds also get some privacy.
At first I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a pity, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downward into the garden.
Maybe I'll do that later, if/when I set up more nest boxes with cameras. Especially in areas further away from the house, I probably need that.
Now the camera is offline and I don't know why. It turned off only an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge further three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or maybe less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have battery telemetry. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
